\begin_layout Standard
It is worth contrasting the results obtained above with those for another
 commonly used non-perturbative technique in QFT: the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 expansion.
 The large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 expansion is a systematic expansion of field theories in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the number of fields.
 Surprisingly there are a number of field theories where this limit exists
 and leads to non-trivial insights.
 While the method is not always quantitatively useful in the main practical
 applications, which are quantum chromodynamics with 
\begin_inset Formula $N=3$
\end_inset

 and the linear sigma model
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 meson is very broad and identifying it as a real particle is controversial,
 though there is definitely a pole which can be observed in pion scattering
 amplitudes 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
PDG ref
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Likewise the pseudoscalar 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and charged 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 Higgs components are absorbed by the 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W^{\pm}$
\end_inset

 gauge bosons respectively and are not observed as scalar states.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for the light mesons 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\pi^{0},\pi^{\pm},\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

 or Higgs 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(h,a,\phi^{\pm}\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $N=4$
\end_inset

, it is responsible for numerous theoretical insights and has rendered some
 un-calculable models calculable and yielded exact non-perturbative results
 in the case of supersymmetric and low dimensional field theories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main idea of the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 approximation is that in the limit of a large number of fields, composites
 of the fields such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}\phi_{a}$
\end_inset

 become self-averaging by the central limit theorem and their behaviour
 is essentially classical.
 The method is not the same as a simple loop expansion, however, as loops
 often contain sums over field components which give factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, partially compensating small couplings.
 Excellent introductory lectures on the method are found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Coleman1985"

\end_inset

 and an extensive modern review in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Moshe2003"

\end_inset

.
 The application of the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 method to the 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 model has a long history as can be seen from the previous references.
 Particularly relevant to this section are the connection to the 2PI method,
 which was published by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Petropoulos2004"

\end_inset

 in essentially the form given here, and the contrast with the SI-2PI method
 which was originally studied by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mao2014"

\end_inset

.
 This section will only consider the leading order of the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 expansion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see how the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 method works in the present case consider again the unimproved 2PI equations
 of motion 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fin-2PI-HF-vev-eom"

\end_inset

-
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:fin-2PI-HF-H-eom"

\end_inset

 reproduced here:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =-v\left(m^{2}+\frac{\lambda}{6}v^{2}+\left(N-1\right)\frac{\hbar\lambda}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\frac{\hbar\lambda}{2}\mathcal{T}_{H}^{\mathrm{fin}}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),\\
m_{G}^{2} & =m^{2}+\frac{\lambda}{6}v^{2}+\frac{\hbar\lambda}{6}\left(N+1\right)\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\frac{\hbar\lambda}{6}\mathcal{T}_{H}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),\\
m_{H}^{2} & =m^{2}+\frac{\lambda}{2}v^{2}+\frac{\hbar\lambda}{6}\left(N-1\right)\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\frac{\hbar\lambda}{2}\mathcal{T}_{H}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset

One now makes a systematic expansion of these equations in powers of 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

.
 Obviously in order to obtain a sensible limit it is necessary to send 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to0$
\end_inset

 as well, otherwise the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}$
\end_inset

 terms dominate and cannot be matched against any other terms.
 However, in order to obtain a non-trivial limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 cannot vanish too fast, so one is forced to take 
\begin_inset Formula $g\equiv\lambda N$
\end_inset

 a constant in the 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 limit.
 In order to obtain a broken symmetry phase it is also necessary to take
 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}\sim\mathcal{O}\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 which can be motivated, for example, by a consideration of the central
 limit theorem with 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}=\left\langle \phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right\rangle =\left\langle \phi_{1}^{2}\right\rangle +\cdots+\left\langle \phi_{N}^{2}\right\rangle \sim N$
\end_inset

.
 The equations of motion become
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =-v\left(m^{2}+\frac{g}{N}\frac{v^{2}}{6}+\frac{\hbar g}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\frac{g}{N}\left(-\frac{\hbar}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\frac{\hbar}{2}\mathcal{T}_{H}^{\mathrm{fin}}\right)\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),\\
m_{G}^{2} & =m^{2}+\frac{g}{N}\frac{v^{2}}{6}+\frac{\hbar g}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\frac{g}{N}\left(\frac{\hbar}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\frac{\hbar}{6}\mathcal{T}_{H}^{\mathrm{fin}}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right),\\
m_{H}^{2} & =m^{2}+\frac{g}{N}\frac{v^{2}}{2}+\frac{\hbar g}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\frac{g}{N}\left(-\frac{\hbar}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\frac{\hbar}{2}\mathcal{T}_{H}^{\mathrm{fin}}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now a comment on an important technicality.
 While 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\to0$
\end_inset

 naively sends the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 terms to zero, these terms contain loops which contain sums over 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(N\right)$
\end_inset

 indices which partially compensate the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 It is not immediately obvious that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 terms can be consistently neglected in the equations of motion.
 It is a non-trivial fact, the proof of which is too much of a combinatorial
 aside to give here (see below for another method which bypasses this technicali
ty altogether), that the maximum amount of compensation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(\lambda^{2}\right)\to\mathcal{O}\left(g^{2}/N\right)$
\end_inset

, so that the higher order graphs can be consistently neglected to leading
 order in 
\begin_inset Formula $g/N$
\end_inset

.
 As a result,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
0 & =-v\left(m^{2}+\frac{g}{N}\frac{v^{2}}{6}+\frac{\hbar g}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{g}{N}\right),\\
m_{G}^{2} & =m^{2}+\frac{g}{N}\frac{v^{2}}{6}+\frac{\hbar g}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{g}{N}\right),\\
m_{H}^{2} & =m^{2}+\frac{g}{N}\frac{v^{2}}{2}+\frac{\hbar g}{6}\mathcal{T}_{G}^{\mathrm{fin}}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{g}{N}\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the first equation of motion is now
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
0=-vm_{G}^{2}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{g}{N}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

i.e.
 Goldstone's theorem holds to leading order in the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 expansion.
 Then in the broken phase 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{H}^{2}=\frac{g}{N}\frac{v^{2}}{3}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{g}{N}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and the critical temperature
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\star}=\sqrt{\frac{12\bar{v}^{2}}{\hbar N}}+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{1}{N}\right),
\]

\end_inset

such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m_{H}^{2}=\bar{m}_{H}^{2}\left(1-\frac{T^{2}}{T_{\star}^{2}}\right)+\mathcal{O}\left(\frac{g}{N}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Again, a second order phase transition is found and Goldstone's theorem
 is satisfied.
 However, the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 estimate for the critical temperature is larger than the symmetry improved
 value by a factor 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\left(N+2\right)/N}$
\end_inset

 which is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{3/2}\approx1.22$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N=4$
\end_inset

, accurate to the expected 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1/N\right)=25\%$
\end_inset

.
 This makes the critical temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $\approx162\ \mathrm{MeV}$
\end_inset

 for the numerical values used previously.
 This difference is the due to the neglect of the Higgs boson thermal contributi
on, which is indeed swamped by Goldstone modes as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Thus the leading large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 approximation has several qualitative similarities to the symmetry improved
 2PIEA, and is quantitatively consistent with it to the expected 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1/N\right)$
\end_inset

 accuracy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are some important qualitative differences however.
 First, the Goldstone theorem is lost at higher orders in 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

, while the SI-2PIEA explicitly enforces it at all orders.
 Second, the contribution of the Higgs to the phase transition thermodynamics
 is totally ignored in the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 approximation, while it is included fully self-consistently in the SI-2PIEA.
 Third, the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 approximation only resums 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and is not fully self-consistent in the sense that all possible Feynman
 diagram topologies with skeletons of a given order are fully resummed,
 but the SI-2PIEA computes all of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{ab}\propto\left\langle \phi_{a}\phi_{b}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 full self-consistently and hence is a more accurate method when applicable.
 Finally, the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 approximation is more natural in the sense that it does not rely upon any
 
\emph on
ad hoc
\emph default
 modification of the effective action, unlike the artificially imposed Ward
 identities of the SI-2PIEA.
 This means that when a large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 limit exists in a given field theory, it is fairly well behaved.
 However, the fact that the SI-2PIEA is constrained leads to difficulties
 in certain truncations (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-Two-Loop-Solution"

\end_inset

) and out of equilibrium (see Chapter 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "chap:chap5"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is another way to see the above results that does not rely on any
 special argument that the Hartree-Fock truncation is consistent to leading
 order in 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

.
 Start with the partition functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Z\left[J\right]=\int\mathcal{D}\left[\phi\right]\exp\left[\frac{i}{\hbar}\left(\frac{1}{2}\phi_{a}\left(-\square-m^{2}\right)\phi_{a}-\frac{\lambda}{4!}\left(\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right)^{2}+J_{a}\phi_{a}\right)\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and note that multiplying by a 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

-independent overall factor of the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\text{const.}=\int\mathcal{D}\left[\sigma\right]\exp\left[\frac{i}{\hbar}\frac{3}{2\lambda}\left(\sigma-\frac{\lambda}{3!}\phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right)^{2}\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

has no physical effect.
 (Also note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \sigma\right\rangle =\frac{\lambda}{3!}\left\langle \phi_{a}\phi_{a}\right\rangle \sim\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The new term has the effect of introducing a new field 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

