\begin_layout Standard
For the present purposes it is convenient to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a}=\left(\pi_{1},\cdots,\pi_{N-1},h\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

s are the Goldstone modes and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is the Higgs mode, and only integrate over the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

s.
 It is also convenient to take 
\begin_inset Formula $J_{a}=\left(0,\cdots,0,J\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{\mathrm{eff}}\left[\pi,h,\sigma\right]=\frac{1}{2}\pi_{a}\left(-\square-m^{2}-\sigma\right)\pi_{a}+\frac{1}{2}h\left(-\square-m^{2}\right)h+Jh+\frac{3}{2\lambda}\sigma^{2}-\frac{1}{2}\sigma h^{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Performing the functional integral over the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

s gives an effective action for the 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 fields, given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left[\frac{i}{\hbar}S_{\mathrm{eff}}\left[h,\sigma\right]\right]=\int\mathcal{D}\left[\pi\right]\exp\left[\frac{i}{\hbar}S_{\mathrm{eff}}\left[\pi,h,\sigma\right]\right]$
\end_inset

, which gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
S_{\mathrm{eff}}\left[h,\sigma\right]=\frac{i\hbar}{2}\left(N-1\right)\mathrm{Tr}\ln\left(-\square-m^{2}-\sigma\right)+\frac{1}{2}h\left(-\square-m^{2}\right)h+Jh+\frac{3N}{2g}\sigma^{2}-\frac{1}{2}\sigma h^{2}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Considering that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\sim\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h\sim\mathcal{O}\left(\sqrt{N}\right)$
\end_inset

 and one can take 
\begin_inset Formula $J\sim\mathcal{O}\left(\sqrt{N}\right)$
\end_inset

, then the entire action is proportional to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 in the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 limit, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\mathrm{eff}}\left[h,\sigma\right]\to N\tilde{S}_{\mathrm{eff}}\left[h,\sigma\right]$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

, where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{S}_{\mathrm{eff}}\left[h,\sigma\right]=\frac{i\hbar}{2}\mathrm{Tr}\ln\left(-\square-m^{2}-\sigma\right)+\frac{1}{2N}h\left(-\square-m^{2}\right)h+\frac{Jh}{N}+\frac{3}{2g}\sigma^{2}-\frac{1}{2N}\sigma h^{2},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The effect of the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 limit in the functional integral 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\int\mathcal{D}\left[h,\sigma\right]\exp\left[\frac{i}{\hbar}N\tilde{S}_{\mathrm{eff}}\left[h,\sigma\right]\right],
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hbar\to0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the classical limit.
 To leading order in 
\begin_inset Formula $1/N$
\end_inset

, then, the dynamics are determined by the 
\emph on
classical
\emph default
 solution of the equations of motion following from 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{S}_{\mathrm{eff}}\left[h,\sigma\right]$
\end_inset

.
 These are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\square+m^{2}+\sigma\right)h & =J,\\
\frac{i\hbar}{2}\mathrm{Tr}\left(-\square-m^{2}-\sigma\right)^{-1} & =\frac{3}{g}\sigma-\frac{1}{2N}h^{2}.
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking for uniform solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $h\left(x\right)=v$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma\left(x\right)=\sigma$
\end_inset

 in the physical limit 
\begin_inset Formula $J=0$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(m^{2}+\sigma\right)v & =0,\\
\frac{i\hbar}{2}\int_{k}\frac{1}{k^{2}-\left(m^{2}+\sigma\right)} & =\frac{3}{g}\sigma-\frac{1}{2N}v^{2}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

In the broken phase the first equation gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma=-m^{2}$
\end_inset

, and one recognises that after renormalisation the second equation is just
 the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 gap equation obtained previously for the Goldstone with 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}=m^{2}+\sigma$
\end_inset

 as the Goldstone mass.
 Substituting 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}-m^{2}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 above one indeed recovers the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 gap equation and the Goldstone theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{G}^{2}v=0$
\end_inset

 in both phases.
 The advantage of this method via transformations of the functional integral
 rather than a direct expansion of the equations of motion is that the systemati
cs of the large 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 expansion are clearer.
 In particular, it is now obvious that the gap equations obtained are strictly
 valid to order 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}\left(1/N\right)$
\end_inset

 without having to worry about the combinatorics of higher order self-energy
 graphs.
 The disadvantage of this method is that the connection to the 2PIEA is
 less clear.
\end_layout

